The Real Estate Developers Association of Nigeria (REDAN) has implored Muslim faithfuls across the country to use this period of Ramadan and assist the less- privileged whose conditions were worsened by the economic and social disruptions caused by Covid-19 pandemic. President of REDAN, Alhaji Aliyu Orono Wamakko disclosed this in his Ramadan message to Nigerians, adding that Ramadan is one of the five pillars of Islam and a special period to seek for Allah’s favour and mercy through prayer and fasting. He stated that this year’s Ramadan is happening at the most unusual time when mankind is contending with the deadly Covid-19 pandemic that shut down the economy and entire social life worldwide. According to him, “As part of measures to combat the pandemic, governments across the globe had directed its citizens to adhere strictly to social distance and avoid large gatherings, including congregational lectures or prayers which are some of the dominant features of the holy month of Ramadan”. He pointed out that the Covid-19 pandemic also affected the “I’tikaf”, which is the usual seclusion in the mosques during the holyY month, as Muslims were advised to observe it in their homes. Wamakko was optimistic that the rules were part of the sacrifices that Muslims are expected to make so that Nigeria would prevail against the ruthless invisible enemy called Covid-19. He however urged the Muslim community and Nigerians generally to comply with the directives issued by the relevant government and religious authorities in a bid to contain the spread of Covid-19. The president added, “I also urge Nigerians to pray for our health workers and other caregivers who are at the front line of the fight against COVID-19 as well as seek for divine guidance to enable our leaders take the right decisions especially in this trying time for the comfort and well-being of the people”. He tasked Muslims to use the holy month and seek for Allah’s mercy through prayer and fasting.